1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,089
The other fellow does not become too important relative to you in your thinking.

2
00:00:05,520 --> 00:00:14,450
The other fellow might look frightfully big, frightfully important, but remember, he is still a human being with essentially the same interests,

3
00:00:14,480 --> 00:00:17,329
desires, and problems as you.

4
00:00:18,559 --> 00:00:19,170
Two.

5
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:22,130
Develop an understanding attitude.

6
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:27,650
People who want figuratively to bite you, growl at you, pick on you,

7
00:00:27,760 --> 00:00:30,690
and otherwise chop you down are not rare.

8
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:38,530
If you're not prepared for people like that, they can punch big holes in your confidence and make you feel completely defeated.

9
00:00:38,799 --> 00:00:45,569
You need a defense against the adult bully, the fellow who likes to throw his meager weight around.

10
00:00:46,080 --> 00:00:55,650
A few months ago, at the reservations desk of a Memphis hotel, I saw an excellent demonstration of the right way to handle folks like this.

11
00:00:56,240 --> 00:01:01,730
It was shortly after 5 p.m., and the hotel was busy registering new guests.

12
00:01:01,840 --> 00:01:06,130
The fellow ahead of me gave his name to the clerk in a commanding way.

13
00:01:06,320 --> 00:01:10,690
The clerk said, Yes, sir, Mr. R. We have a fine single for you.

14
00:01:11,280 --> 00:01:12,130
Single?

15
00:01:12,320 --> 00:01:13,490
shouted the fellow.

16
00:01:13,680 --> 00:01:15,089
I ordered a double.

17
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:19,329
The clerk said, very politely, Let me check, sir.

18
00:01:19,520 --> 00:01:26,849
He pulled the guest's reservation from the file and said, I'm sorry, sir, your telegram specified a single.

19
00:01:27,039 --> 00:01:31,250
I'd be happy to put you in a double room, sir, if we had any available,

20
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:33,010
but we simply do not.

21
00:01:33,520 --> 00:01:39,809
Then the irate customer said, I don't care what the H that piece of paper says,

22
00:01:39,840 --> 00:01:41,170
I want a double.

23
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:45,329
Then he started in with that, do you know who I am, bit,

24
00:01:45,440 --> 00:01:50,450
followed with, I'll have you fired, you'll see, I'll have you fired.

25
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:56,930
As best he could, under the verbal tornado, the young clerk injected, Sir,

26
00:01:56,960 --> 00:02:01,010
we're terribly sorry, but we acted on your instructions.

27
00:02:01,600 --> 00:02:12,450
Finally, the customer, really furious now, said, I wouldn't stay in the best suite in this blank-blank hotel now that I know how badly managed it is,

28
00:02:12,640 --> 00:02:14,130
and stormed out.

29
00:02:14,799 --> 00:02:22,210
I stepped up to the desk, thinking the clerk, who had taken one of the worst public tongue lashings I'd seen in some time,

30
00:02:22,320 --> 00:02:23,569
would be upset.

31
00:02:23,760 --> 00:02:29,010
Instead, he greeted me with one of the finest good evening sirs I'd ever heard.

32
00:02:29,280 --> 00:02:33,490
As he went through the routine of processing my room, I said to him,

33
00:02:33,920 --> 00:02:37,970
I certainly admire the way you handled yourself just a moment ago.

34
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:40,609
You have tremendous temper control.

35
00:02:41,120 --> 00:02:45,410
Well, sir, he said, I really can't get mad at a fellow like that.

36
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:47,890
You see, he really isn't mad at me.

37
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:49,730
I was just the scapegoat.

38
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:54,930
The poor fellow may be in bad trouble with his wife, or his business may be off,

39
00:02:54,960 --> 00:02:59,809
or maybe he feels inferior and this was his golden chance to feel like a wheel.

40
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,130
I'm just the guy who gave him a chance to get something out of his system.

41
00:03:04,480 --> 00:03:09,010
The clerk added, underneath, he's probably a very nice guy.

42
00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:10,530
Most folks are.

43
00:03:11,520 --> 00:03:19,089
Walking toward the elevators, I caught myself repeating aloud, Underneath he's probably a very nice guy.

44
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:20,849
Most folks are.

45
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:26,690
Remember those two short sentences next time someone declares war on you.

46
00:03:26,880 --> 00:03:28,130
Hold your fire.

47
00:03:28,400 --> 00:03:35,250
The way to win in situations like this is to let the other fellow blow his stack and then forget it.

